NEW YORK (AP) — U.S. stocks are heading for records on Friday after  an update on inflation  came in a bit less painful than feared. The S&P 500 rose 1% and was on track to top  its all-time high , which was set earlier this month. The Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 529 points, or 1.1%, as of 2:05 p.m. Eastern time, and the Nasdaq composite was 1.3% higher. Both were also rising toward records.  The data on inflation is encouraging because it could mean less pain for lower- and middle-income households struggling with  still-high increases in prices  every month. Even more importantly for Wall Street, it could also clear the way for the Federal Reserve to keep cutting interest rates in hopes of giving a boost to  the slowing job market . The Fed  just cut its main interest rate  last month for the first time this year, but it’s been hesitant to promise more relief because lower rates can make inflation worse, beyond goosing the economy and prices for investments. Following the inflation report, traders upped bets to a near certainty that the Fed will cut rates at its next two meetings, including one next week.  



